node.text: Wimshurst Electrostatic Generator: this device uses two counter rotating disks of metal pads to separate charge via induction. The repulsion felt by electrons as the triangle plates pass by each other pushes charge to flow across two conducting rods, one on each side, which allows the charge to stack up. This excess charge is then stored in old fashioned cylindrical capacitors (Leyden Jars) until the resulting 30,000+ Volts is achieved to jump the air gap. This device goes back to  1883- invented by James Wimshurst. ➡️ Follow the link in my profile for info on where to get this device and other amazing items featuresd here on @physicsfun #physics #physicsfun #physicstoy #electromagnetism #wimshurst #wimshurstmachine #electrostatic #electrostaticgenerator #sciece #sparkgap #leydenjar #capacitor #induction #charge #électrons #scienceisawesome

node.text: 3-Shuttle Trammel of Archimedes: as the shuttles take turns completing their straight line journeys, the end of the crank arm traces an ellipse. This precision 3-shuttle version by the VSauce team came in my @thecuriositybox - made with high quality molded plastic parts that produce very smooth movement- a wonderful addition to my collection! Sometimes sold as a “do nothing machine” or “nothing grinder”, far from doing nothing this simple and crucially important mechanism demonstrates how rotational motion can be converted into translational oscillatory motion- such as how a piston can drive an engine’s crankshaft. ➡️ Follow the link in my profile for info on where to get similar devices and other amazing items featured here on @physicsfun #physics #physicsfun #physicstoy #mathtoy #mathstoy #ellipse #ellipsograph #Archimedes #donothingmachine #trammelofarchimedes #conicsection #oscillator #fourbarlinkage #mechanicalengineering #science #scienceisawesome

node.text: Super Absorbent Polymer: poly-acrylamide polymer crystals are able to absorb up to 200 times their volume of water. Equatorial Bulge Demo: two springy circular rings flatten along their axis of rotation in proportion to the rate of spin in this classic teaching demonstration. This device demonstrates that centripetal accelerations applied to an elastic sphere will cause it to bulge at the equator- becoming an oblate spheroid.  Isaac Newton predicted that given the Earth’s rotation, the radius to the equator would be larger than the radius to the North Pole by 1 part in 230. He was correct! (although overestimated slightly- swipe for description) Modern measurements indicate 1 part in 294.7. Question: At what location on Earth could you stand on land and be furtherest from its center? Mt Everest is a good guess, but the correct answer is the top of Mt Chimborazo in Ecuador. (swipe twice for details) Although Everest is higher above sea level, the equatorial bulge puts the top of Chimborazo a 2.2 km further into space from the center of the Earth. ➡️ Follow the link in my profile for more info and details on where to get many of the amazing items featured here on @physicsfun #physics #physicsfun #physicstoy #physicsdemo #oblatesphereoid #equator #equitorialbulge #chimborazo #everest #centripetal #angularmomentum #centripetalacceleration #science #rotatingearth #scienceisawesome

node.text: The Square Wave: one of my favorite interactive kinetic sculptures from the mind of artist Ivan Black. Waves propagate through the 24 interlocking right angle metal rods, folding the structure into a tight curl- and a reverse snap will bring it back to the initial flat square state. An important design feature is that each right angle rod is limited to move through about 45 degrees, and all through parallel axes, allowing for the beautiful rotational wave motion via a cascade of angular momentum transfer. See other amazing creations by Ivan on his IG stream: @ivanblacksculpture ➡️ Follow the link in my profile for info to purchase a Square Wave and find other amazing items featured here on @physicsfun #kineticart #angularmomentum #physicstoy #physics #rotation #squarewave #rotationalinertia #physicsfun #art #science #scienceisawesome

Three AA batteries and a small motor power the transport assembly. ➡️ Follow the link in my profile for more info and where to get this Orb Drop kit and other amazing items featured here on @physicsfun #physics #physicstoy #gravity #gravitywell #orbdrop #angularmomentum #kinetic #kineticart #kineticenergy #marblerun #science #scienceisawesome

node.text: The FluoroSphere: intricate and dynamic lights shows are produced within an elegant glass sphere as fluorescent dyes in mineral oil slowly mix into room temperature water. Ultraviolet LEDs (in the base on which the sphere rests) make the dyes glow brightly and reveal the initial nondiffusive mixing structure which includes the phenomena of drops, plumes, and other features of Rayleigh-Taylor instabilities. Shown here, slightly sped up, is the first 8 minutes or so of the process which takes up to half an hour to mix evenly. The green light is characteristic of the famous fluorescein dye. ➡️ Follow the link in my profile for info on where to get this science kit and other amazing items featured here on @physicsfun #physics #physicsfun #physicstoy #fluorescent #fluorescence #quantummechanics #stokesshift #fluorescein #viscosity #viscousflow #reynoldsnumber #rayleightaylorinstability #mixing #polymer #turbulence #science #scienceisawesome

node.text: Dymaxion Map: today some math fun with this unique mapping of the Earth where the globe is projected onto an icosahedron and then unfolded onto two dimensions. Invented by the famous architect R. Buckminster Fuller, the Dymaxion projection map is designed such that it does not have a “right way up” and showing the continents as “one island Earth”. This mapping also produces less distortion of relative areas and shapes- note here that Greenland looks, correctly, much smaller than Africa- unlike what is seen on many world maps where they look the same size. This version, designed by Brendan Ravenhill, uses flat magnets to allow a very satisfying transformation between the flat 2D net and the 3D icosahedron “globe”. ➡️ Follow the link in my profile for more info on where to get this map and other amazing items featured here on @physicsfun #map #earth #globe #cartography #projection #mapprojection #buckminsterfuller #dymaxion #geometry #platonicsolid #icosahedron #physics #physicstoy #physicsfun #science #mathtoy #mathstoy #scienceisawesome
